Soccer Analysis Project¶

Project by Saketh Kura¶

Introduction¶

I have been recently watching the World Cup 2022 and found the games to be quite exhilerating. Now, we are waiting to see who will win this world cup (I hope it is Argentina). But anyways, watching soccer (or football) has led me interested in the overall game, especially into the players. We are all aware of some of the top players like Lionel Messi and Christian Ronaldo, but what makes them such strong players? We will look into many questions that break down their player stats and see who is the best at certain skillsets. Ultimately, we will looking into which factors help determine how good a player really is.

We will be looking at FIFA data for soccer players because we can get insights into specific features such as their strengths and weakness of the teams thats play in the FIFA World Cup. We can get a sense of which kind of players will perform the best in an international setting as well as understand what strategies different teams may utlize. The goal is to see which soccer stats are effective in determining a soccer player's overall rating. With these features, we can predit a new soccer player's potential rating and and analyze how teams will perform.

Data Collection¶

We will be looking at a dataset named "FIFA 2022 complete player dataset" from Kaggle, an online platform where users upload and download certain datasets. This dataset contains the information from "Career Mode" in FIFA 15,16,16,17,18,19,20,21,and 22. For the purpose of this tutorial, we will only be looking FIFA 22 dataset to get the most up to date information about the players. The data had been scrapped from sofifa.com, a website dedicated to updating sport stats and information regarding individual soccer players around the world. Here is the link to the dataset if you are more interested in how the dataset is made, click this.

Data Management¶

For this tutorial, we will only be looking at a few features and analyze them to see how impactful they are to the overall rating of the player. This is because not only does this dataset have unrelated information such as URLs to logos, photos, and stat websites, but we will try to simplify the data analysis as much as possible so we can learn the most about the data. If were to include all of the columns into our analysis, we could be exploring our data for days. So, let's focus on only a few relevant aspects that can relate to a player's overall rating.

Let's look at the following player skills: pace, shooting, passing, dribbling, defending, and physique. There are many other fields that we can look into, but I chose these because these the are primary skills related to soccer. According to the Soccer Training Guide, the most important skills are passing, receiving, trapping(receiving the ball while standing still), and shooting. I incorporated most of these skills, and added defending because a soccer player should be well rounded and not just focused on offense and and physique is an important measurement as to how fit a player is, meaning they are capable of physically performing better than others.

We won't be needing the player's names because we will ultimately be observing how certain stats affect a player's overall score, so we will not be conducting analysis on individual players, but rather players in the entire dataset.

Overall, we will be looking at the following features to predict a player's overall rating:

  • Nationality
  • Age
  • Shooting
  • Passing
  • Dribbling
  • Defending
  • Physique

We need to extract these certain columns from our dataset. Also, if we take a look at the physique column, it is misspelled, so we will fix the spelling in the updated dataset. We will include the player_position column not as a feature, but as as category to classify for later.

Since some players have multiple player positions, we will pick the first one because that is their preferred one.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

To make the plots in the tutorial, we will be using the seaborn library. This library is very friendly with pandas and is capable of generating beautiful plots with only a few lines of code. This will be helpful for us as it does not overcomplicated the plotting process. Matplotlib is another option for plotting data, but I think seaborn plots have a better appearance due to their design and color choices.

First, let's conduct some analysis on the special dataset. I want to know how much these nations pay for their professional players. Do they range and vary between nation? Let's find out!

We will making a dictionary that keeps track of the wage list for each country. That way, we can quickly get the average by summing up the wages then dividing by their length of the list. We will also get the counts for preferred feet. We will then make a bar graph out of these datasets. We won't be using Poland,

In [9]:
#Creating wage lists for each country, where each player from that country's wage is 
#in that list
sum_wages = {}

for i in ordered_nations:
    sum_wages[i] = []

for r in special.itertuples(index=False):
    wage = r[2]
    nat = r[1]
    sum_wages[nat].append(wage) 
    
for i in sum_wages:
    if len(sum_wages[i]) != 0:
        sum_wages[i]  = sum(sum_wages[i])/len(sum_wages[i])
    else:
        sum_wages[i]  = 0

Now, let's make a barplot for the weekly wages. I did not use wages because these can be negotiated/external factors that can decide that value. Therefore, it is not necessarily a good indicator of how a player is. We will be using plt's bar function. We are using plt for this barplot because seaborn is a bit stubborn when working with dictonaries, while plt is capable of working with more flexible data structures. Because the nationalities are long, we will abbreviate them with two letters. To learn more about plt's bar, click this.

Let's do some preliminary analysis and look at the general distributions of age and overall rating. We can ask questions like:

  • What is the average age of a professional soccer player?
  • Are there more young players than older ones?
  • What is the average overall rating of a professional soccer player?
  • What kinds of players are there?

We will be plotting histograms for age and overall rating. Histograms show the frequency of numerical data point. We also have the option of grouping the numerical variable into intervals and get their frequency as well. They are an appealing plot to display the distribution of a single variable. To learn more about how to use histograms in seaborn, click this.

For the age distribution, it is slightly right skewed, so the majority of the players are to the younger side. In fact, after 40, there are little to no players in sight. Nations have all kinds of players, so we can ask some questions about them:

  • What makes each nation different?
  • Do some nations have faster players or better shooters?
  • Which nation has the best players overall?

To understand the distributions for each of the top 15 nations, we will be creating a violin plot for each of the skills. A violin plot shows the distribution of numerical data over a categorical variable. It is similar to a box and whisker plot, but instead of showing the lines, the distribution is displayed with a smooth curve. The curve is generated based on the sample size, so to make it as accurate as possible, we need an ample amount of data points. By selecting the top 15 nations, we will have enough data points to make the curve meaningful. We are also using violin plots because they can give insight into the modes of the distribution, potentially multiple modes. To learn more about violin plots, click this.

In our tutorial, we will be using the nationality as the categorical variable and observe the distributions through each of the skill variables.

From the age violin plot, we can see how the average age for playing professional soccer is between 20 and 30, but that varies from nation to nation. For most of the countries like Argentina, France, and Spain, their distributions are skewed right, so the majority of the players are on the younger side. This is expected as the peak age for playing professional soccer is around 25 according the Athletic. Brazil's multimodal distribution shows that many of its players are of roughly 20, 24, and 30 years old. Japan seems to have a player/players in the 50+ range.

Standardization¶

When working with numerical data, it is important to standardize it because this can help with comparing different variables more easily and locate potential outliers in the data. Below we will standard our skill/physical numerical features.

In [20]:
def standardize(name):
    skills[name] = (skills[name] - skills[name].mean()) / skills[name].std()

for c in ["age", "shooting", "passing", "dribbling", "defending", 'physique']:
    standardize(c)

Hypothesis Testing¶

Feature Correlations¶

Now, we will look into how the different features correlate with one another and see their level of strength. To do this, we will make a heatmap of the features. Heat maps create a square grid, where the columns and rows are the features, and each cell in the grid find the correlation between those two features. The color represents the strength of correlation, where typically a strong correlation correlates to dark color. This map will help us observe the relationships between the features. We will be using seaborn to make the heat map. To learn more about heat maps, click this.

In [22]:
data = skills.drop('nationality_name', axis=1)
data = data.reset_index(drop=True)
sns.heatmap(data.corr(),cmap="YlGnBu");

When looking at the heat map, we can positive and negative correlations for different pairs of features. We ignore the diagonal because each cell find the correlation between the same variable, so it will always be strongly correlated. When looking overall rating, it holds a positive correlation with the rest of the features, being more strongly correlated with passing and dribbling. For negative correlation, the strongest cells are between shooting and defending. This makes sense because these features are opposite, as shooters are offensive and defender are defensive. There is little to no correlation between physique and dribbling and physique and shooting. This was unexpecting because to dribble or even shoot, this requires having a good power and speed, which are a part of a good physique.

We should also check to see the correlation coefficients between the rest of the features and the overall rating and see their probability value. The importance of the probability value is to see how significant the correlation is. If the probabliy is less than 0.05, then we can rule the correlation as significant. To do this, we will run a Pearson's test on each of the pairs. Pearson's Test are done to determine the linear correlation between two variables. Althought the variables are not directly linear, they are still a good approach to determining correlation.

To run the Pearson's Test, we will be using scipy, a Python library that is focused on creating functions for data modeling and analysis. In our case, we will use it to run the Pearson's test.

To learn more about Pearson's Test and when to use it, click this.

Let's run the Pearson's Correlation Test for each of the numerical independent variables and see it's correlation with the overall rating.

Now we will create the model. We will implement the Holdout Validation, where we hold out a certain percentage of the data to later test with. In our case, we will holdout 20% of our data to test with. We first need to split our data into a training and testing set. We will use this validation approach because it is simple to implement and runs quickly. We do this so we can have an indepdent set for the model to be tested with later. We split the data into the traing and testing set, we then fit the model based on the training data, then we predict the values on the test set. To learn more about Holdout Validation, click this.

To determine how well the predicted overall ratings were with the actual overall ratings, we will use the mean squared error (MSE). This measurement calculates average squared differences between the prediction and actual values. I chose this because it penalizes large errors more than small ones. To learn more about Multiple Regression Model and the r2 score, click this.

Classification¶

Now, we will try to classify soccer players on their positions based on their skill/physical scores.

Preprocessing + Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In [31]:
sns.countplot(x=mldata["player_positions"])
Out[31]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='player_positions', ylabel='count'>

This a frequency plot of the different player positions. We can see how uneven the data is. I will keep this distribution because I believe it is important account for this spread. I will first need to convert the position labels into classes by factorizing them.

We will try a Logistic Regression Classifier as a base line and then work with a Random Forest Classifier.

We will not use the R^2 score because it is not a good indicator for non linear data because this score relies on a variance pattern. If the data does not follow that linearity, then the score will not be representative of scoring that model.

We will not use ROC AUC score either because although it is good for multiclass classification, since the classes are pretty imbalanced, it will not be a good measurement.

Instead, we will use Recall and F1 Score to measure.

Recall calculates out of the actual positive, how many did the model classify the positive correctly. This is useful for imbalanced datasets because the scoring is focused on classifying each class itself without considering all of them together.

F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall. Both these factors contribute to the score. It puts an emphasis on classifying the positive classes correctly. Incorporates the importance of reducing false positives and negatives as well. This works well on imbalanced data by incorporating recall.

In [32]:
mldata['classes'] = pd.factorize(mldata['player_positions'])[0]
X = mldata.drop(['overall', 'player_positions', 'classes'], axis=1)
y = mldata['classes']

model = LogisticRegression()

model.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

print("F1 Score: ", f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted'))

Communication of Insights¶

I chose to do a Multiple Linear Regression model and after calculating the score, we got a MSE score of 3.85, while the Random Forest Regression model got a MSE score of 0.46. Random Forest models are more suitable for nonlinear data because it has the freedom of creating more and deep decision trees. When looking at the residual plots, we can see that the model performed well during the middle overall ratings compared to the lower or higher overall ratings. The residual plot helps with locating where the model is doing well and where it is doing poorly. Based on the Pearsons's test, I saw that the greatest correlation coefficient with the overall rating came from passing and dribbling, making these two features the most prominent and most significant features in the model.

With this analysis and learning model, players, managers, teams, and even clubs can understand what makes up a good soccer player and help them identify which features they need to work on. We can continue to help build players and identify their weakness and strengths and to create more exciting teams. National teams for the World Cup expect only the greatest players and as better plays emerge, they will raise their expectations, so players need to figure out what they need to work on and must succeed. Games will become more exciting. I can't wait to see how the next world cup will be, learning more about soccer teams and players and see who will become the best of the best.
